{"title_page": "Smoking in Sweden", "text_new": "[[Image:Snus.jpg|thumb|275px|Portioned [[snus]] of the [[Sweden|Swedish]] label [[General snus|General]]]]\n'''Smoking in Sweden''' is at a very low prevalence; only 11% of the total Swedish population (8% of men and 10% of women) smoked daily in 2016.<ref name=\"Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten\">{{Cite web\n| url=  https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/folkhalsorapportering-statistik/folkhalsans-utveckling/levnadsvanor/tobaksrokning-daglig/\n| title=  Tobaksr\u00f6kning, daglig\n| publisher=  Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten\n| date=  29 October 2003\n| accessdate =  26 April 2017\n}}</ref> Around another 10% smoke occasionally.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} Smoking has been [[Smoking ban|banned]] in all [[Bar (establishment)|bar]]s and [[restaurant]]s since May 2005.<ref name=\"Smoking curbs\">{{Cite news\n| url=  http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/3758707.stm#europe\n| title= Smoking curbs: The global picture\n| publisher=  [[BBC News]]\n| date=  1 July 2009\n| accessdate= 13 August 2010}}</ref> A majority of [[Swedish people|Swedes]] supported the introduction of the ban.<ref name=\"Smoking curbs\" /> [[Sweden]] was the only [[Europe]]an country to achieve the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] goal of less than 20% daily smoking prevalence among adults by year 2000.<ref name=\"HealthCentral\">{{Cite web\n |url         = http://www.healthcentral.com/drdean/408/60681.html\n |title       = Quit Smoking Swedish Style\n |publisher   = HealthCentral.com\n |date        = 29 October 2003\n |accessdate  = 13 August 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20101112015943/http://www.healthcentral.com/drdean/408/60681.html\n |archivedate = 12 November 2010\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> Sweden has a high level of use of [[smokeless tobacco]], specifically a moist snuff product called '[[snus]]', which some Swedes have used as a replacement for smoking.<ref name=\"HealthCentral\" />\n\n==References==\n{{